﻿A 14-day-old boy was referred to our clinic because of dysmorphic facial features (Figure 1A). He was born by cesarean section that was performed because of breech presentation at term. He had an apparently healthy elder brother and there was no relevant family history. There was no consanguinity between parents.
Birth weight was 3100 g (25–50th centile), height was 47 cm (3–10th centile) and head circumference was 34 cm (50th centile). Physical examination revealed a large anterior fontanel of 3.5×5 cm, large metopic suture, widow’s peak, hypertelorism, low-back rotated ears, broad-depressed nasal bridge, short nose, high arched palate, brachydactyly, bilateral simian line and unilateral cryptorchidism. The complete blood count, liver enzymes, electrolytes, renal function tests, thyroid function tests, creatine kinase, alkaline phosphatase, 25-hydroxyvitamin D3 lactic acid, pyruvic acid, ammonia and tandem mass were normal. Karyotype was normal 46,XY. Ophthalmologic examination, eye fundoscopy and hearing test were intended to be normal. Abdominal ultrasonography and electrocardiogram were evaluated as normal. X-ray radiography revealed relatively short proximal long bones (femur and humerus), with enlarged diaphysis and brachydactyly of hands. X-ray craniography, cranial ultrasonography and cranial scintigraphy imaging showed a large sagittal suture, a large metopic suture and a large anterior fontanel. Cranial magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) was normal. With these findings the case clinically diagnosed as Robinow syndrome.
When the patient as 20 months old, his weight was 10 kg (25–50th centile) and his height was 79 cm (10–25th centile). At follow-up at 20 months of age, the anterior fontanel was closed (Figure 1B). He was operated on because of cryptorchidism. Mental-motor development was normal. Shawl scrotum was noted. Control radiographies of long bones were revealed to be normal. There were no additional findings at physical examination but facial changes and normal radiographs of long bones canalized to change the diagnosis to ASS.
